{0 PDB and CodeView concepts}

This page explains what a PDB file actually contains, why it is laid
out the way it is, and how the modules in this library map onto the
on-disk structures. It assumes no prior knowledge of Windows debugging
formats.

{1 The big picture}

When a Windows compiler builds an executable it can optionally emit
debug information so a debugger like WinDbg or Visual Studio can map
machine addresses back to source. Unlike Linux and macOS, where the
debug information is bundled inside the executable in DWARF sections,
Windows stores most of it in a separate file with the [.pdb]
extension. The executable holds only a small reference (a GUID and an
age counter) that lets the debugger find and validate the matching
PDB.

A PDB file contains, broadly:

- a description of every compilation unit (called a {b module} in PDB
  terminology) that went into the binary
- the {b types} defined by those modules e.g structs, unions, enums,
  pointers, function signatures
- the {b symbols} -- functions, globals, locals, parameters, labels
- line-number tables and file-checksum tables mapping ranges of
  machine code back to source files
- hash-based indices for fast symbol lookup
- stack-unwinding tables so the debugger can compute backtraces

The CodeView format is the on-disk shape of the type records and
symbol records themselves. The PDB format is the container that
organises everything else around them.

{1 The MSF container}

At the lowest level a PDB file is not "a PDB" rather it is a
Multi-Stream File (MSF). MSF is essentially a tiny page-based virtual
filesystem.

The file is divided into fixed-size {b blocks} (typically 4 KiB,
sometimes 512 / 1024 / 2048 bytes). Logical {b streams} are stored as
ordered lists of block indices, so a stream can be any size and is not
required to be contiguous on disk. A small {b stream directory} lists
each stream's length and the blocks it occupies. The first block of
the file holds a fixed {b superblock} pointing at the stream directory.

This indirection matters because Microsoft's tooling historically
edited PDBs in place during incremental linking, treating the file as
a paged collection of streams meant a writer could append to one
stream without rewriting the rest. ocaml-pdb only writes complete
PDBs, but it still has to honour the layout to remain compatible.

A small {b Free Page Map} (FPM) bitmap marks which blocks are in use
versus free. The reader implementations can mostly ignore it, but a writer
has to emit it correctly or tooling like [llvm-pdbutil] will reject
the file.

In code:

- {!Pdb.Msf} reads an MSF file and exposes each stream as a
  bigarray slice.
- {!Pdb.Msf_write} accumulates streams and lays them out into
  blocks on finalize.

Once you have the streams, the rest of the library reads or writes
the {e contents} of each stream. The MSF layer never inspects them.

{1 The fixed streams}

Stream indices 0..4 always have the same meaning in a PDB:

- {b Stream 0} old MSF directory backup. Effectively unused today;
  the library writes a minimal placeholder.
- {b Stream 1} {b PDB Info Stream}. Contains the format version, a
  GUID + age counter that the executable also stores (so the debugger
  can verify it loaded the right PDB), and a map from named streams
  to their indices.
- {b Stream 2} {b TPI Stream}. The Type Index stream: every type
  record (structs, pointers, function signatures, etc.) referenced
  from anywhere in the PDB lives here.
- {b Stream 3} {b DBI Stream}. The Debug Information stream: the
  central directory connecting modules, section contributions, source
  files, and the stream indices of the GSI/PSI/sym-record streams.
- {b Stream 4} {b IPI Stream}. The ID stream. Same on-disk format
  as TPI but stores "ID records" rather than type records. The split
  exists for historical reasons.

Beyond stream 4, all other streams are referenced by index from one
of the fixed streams or from the named-stream map. Streams have no
intrinsic meaning, an index 7 might be a module symbol stream in one
PDB and a "/names" string table in another.

{2 The named-stream map}

A handful of streams are looked up by name rather than fixed index.
The named-stream map lives inside the PDB Info Stream (stream 1) and
is a hash table from strings like ["/names"], ["/LinkInfo"],
["/src/headerblock"] to a stream index. ocaml-pdb only uses
["/names"] (see below) but parses any others the input contains.

In code:

- {!Pdb.Pdb_stream} / {!Pdb.Pdb_stream_write} is stream 1.
- {!Pdb.Named_stream_map} is the hash-table format used by stream 1.

{1 Types: the TPI / IPI streams}

The TPI and IPI streams contain a contiguous sequence of CodeView
{b type records}. Each record has a 2-byte length prefix, a 2-byte
leaf kind ([LF_POINTER], [LF_STRUCTURE], [LF_PROCEDURE]), and a
payload. The library exposes each record as a constructor of
{!Pdb.Codeview_types.type_record}.

{2 TypeIndex: how records reference each other}

A CodeView type often refers to another type. A pointer-to-int holds
a TypeIndex naming "int", a function signature holds a TypeIndex for
the return type plus an argument-list TypeIndex, a struct holds a
TypeIndex for its field list.

The wire format encodes both kinds of TypeIndex as a single [u32]:

- Values [< 0x1000] encode a {b built-in primitive} via a packed bit
  layout (integer / float / pointer-to-primitive). There is no record
  on disk for these.
- Values [>= 0x1000] are {b user-defined records} stored in TPI or
  IPI. The value is the record's position in the stream, starting at
  [0x1000] for the first record.

ocaml-pdb wraps this in the {!Pdb.Type_index} variant so the two
cases stay statically distinguishable.

{2 Why two streams: TPI vs IPI}

Microsoft split type-style records (a struct, a function signature)
from ID-style records (a string-id, a function ID naming a specific
function by string) so that the two namespaces could be hashed and
deduplicated independently. The on-disk format is identical, only the
kinds of records found in each stream differ.

In code:

- {!Pdb.Codeview_types} record definitions and per-record
  read/write.
- {!Pdb.Tpi} / {!Pdb.Tpi_write} TPI/IPI stream-level read/write
  (header, record sequence, hash table).
- {!Pdb.Type_index} the TypeIndex variant.
- {!Pdb.Type_merge} de-duplicates identical type records across
  compilation units, rewriting cross-references onto a shared
  numbering. This is what a linker does when combining per-object-file
  TPI streams into a single program-wide TPI.

{1 Symbols and where they live}

A {b symbol record} describes one program entity, a function,
parameter, local variable, global, public, etc. Each record has a
2-byte length prefix, a 2-byte symbol kind, and a payload, just like
type records but in a separate namespace.

Symbols are stored in three different places depending on their
purpose:

- {b Per-module symbol streams.} Each compilation unit has its own
  symbol stream listing the symbols defined or used in that unit:
  function definitions, their parameters and locals, file-static
  variables. These streams are referenced from the DBI stream's
  module list. A debugger that has narrowed a query to a specific
  module reads only that module's stream.
- {b The combined symbol record stream.} A single stream
  concatenating every {b global} and {b public} symbol from every
  module. This is the haystack the GSI/PSI hashes index into.
- {b The DBI module list} itself is not a symbol stream, but it tells
  you which per-module stream to open for each module.

A {b public} is a name that participates in linking (typically a
mangled C++ name with an RVA). A {b global} is a non-linker-visible
entity (a global variable, a constant, a UDT alias). The two have
separate hash tables in the GSI/PSI streams because the lookup
patterns are different.

In code:

- {!Pdb.Codeview_symbols} symbol record definitions and per-record
  read/write.
- {!Pdb.Gsi} / {!Pdb.Gsi_write} the publics and globals hash
  tables that index into the combined sym-record stream.

{1 The DBI stream: gluing it together}

The DBI stream is the central catalog. It contains, in this order:

- a header with format flags and references to the
  publics-hash-stream, globals-hash-stream, and combined-sym-record
  stream indices;
- a {b module list}, one entry per compilation unit, each pointing at
  that module's per-module symbol stream and listing the source files
  it consumed;
- a {b section contributions} substream describing which range of
  each PE section came from which module (so a debugger can find the
  responsible module from an instruction pointer);
- a {b file info} substream listing the source filenames each module
  contributed;
- the {b optional debug header}, a fixed array of stream indices for
  auxiliary streams: FPO data, framedata, OMAP-from-source, OMAP-to-source,
  section headers, exception data, etc. Each slot is [0xFFFF] if the
  corresponding stream is absent.

When the debugger starts up it reads the PDB info stream, then the
DBI stream, then uses the DBI's pointers to find everything else.

In code:

- {!Pdb.Dbi} / {!Pdb.Dbi_write} the DBI stream itself.
- {!Pdb.Debug_subsections} the C13 debug subsections (line tables,
  file checksums, etc.) embedded in per-module symbol streams.

{1 Line tables and the C13 framework}

Mapping a machine address to a source line could in principle be
another flavour of symbol record, but Microsoft instead defined a
small framework for "debug subsections" stored at the end of each
per-module symbol stream. Each subsection has a 4-byte kind, a 4-byte
length, then payload:

- {b Lines} the line-number table for a contiguous range of code.
- {b FileChecksums} per-file checksums and offsets into the
  /names string table.
- {b InlineeLines} line info for inlined function bodies.
- {b StringTable} a per-module string table (rarely used; most
  PDBs use the global /names stream instead).
- {b FrameData} per-function frame layout (the modern replacement
  for the old FPO_DATA stream).
- {b CrossModuleExports} / {b CrossModuleImports} references
  between modules (used by /Zc precompiled headers and similar).

A FileChecksums entry refers to a filename by its offset in the
global /names stream, which is why /names exists as a separate
top-level stream.

In code: {!Pdb.Debug_subsections}.

{1 The global /names string table}

The ["/names"] named stream is a single global table of
NUL-terminated strings. Anywhere in the PDB that wants to refer to a
filename or path stores a u32 offset into /names instead of inlining
the string. Deduplication is built in so adding the same string twice
returns the same offset.

In code: {!Pdb.Pdb_string_table}.

{1 Stack unwinding}

To compute a backtrace the debugger has to know, for any PC, how to
recover the previous frame's PC and stack pointer. On Linux that
information lives in DWARF CFI ([.eh_frame] / [.debug_frame]), on
Windows it lives in the executable's [.xdata] / [.pdata] sections in
a binary-encoded form called {b UNWIND_INFO}. The format differs by
architecture:

- {b x86-64} uses a sequence of small opcodes describing the
  prologue: PUSH RBP, ALLOC 0x20 bytes, SAVE_XMM xmm6 to [rsp+0x40],
  etc. Replaying the opcodes in reverse from any PC inside the
  function recovers the caller's frame.
- {b ARM64} uses a packed bit-field encoding optimised for the
  smaller, more regular ARM calling convention, both ".pdata"-only
  packed form and full ".xdata" form exist.

This information lives in the PE, not the PDB, but the library
parses and writes it for completeness. A debugger needs both the
PDB (to know what the variables are) and the unwind info (to walk
the stack at all).

In code:

- {!Pdb.Unwind} common entry point.
- {!Pdb.Unwind.module-X64} / {!Pdb.Unwind.module-Arm64} the
  per-architecture encoders.

{1 Auxiliary streams}

A few smaller streams round out the format:

- {b /names} the global string table described above.
- {b FPO data} an older per-function frame layout table for x86
  binaries, predating the C13 FrameData subsection. The DBI optional
  debug header has a slot for it.
- {b OMAP} two streams describing an address remapping that
  happens when a tool reorders a binary's basic blocks after initial
  compilation (for example, Microsoft's BBT for profile-guided
  layout). Debugger queries pass through OMAP-from-source so an old
  RVA in source coordinates maps to its new post-reorder RVA.

In code: {!Pdb.Fpo}, {!Pdb.Omap}.

{1 How the modules fit together}

Reading a PDB end-to-end roughly follows:

+ Open the file with {!Pdb.Msf.read} to get the stream collection.
+ Parse stream 1 with {!Pdb.Pdb_stream.parse} to learn the named
  streams (especially [/names]).
+ Parse stream 3 with {!Pdb.Dbi.parse} to learn the modules,
  section contributions, and the indices of the GSI/PSI/sym-record
  and auxiliary streams.
+ Parse streams 2 and 4 with {!Pdb.Tpi.parse_header} +
  {!Pdb.Tpi.parse_type_records} to load the type and ID records.
+ For each module in the DBI, open its symbol stream and call
  {!Pdb.Codeview_symbols.parse_symbol_stream} for symbols, then
  {!Pdb.Debug_subsections.parse_subsections} for line tables.
+ For lookup-by-name, parse the publics/globals streams with
  {!Pdb.Gsi.parse_publics_header} + {!Pdb.Gsi.parse_gsi}.

Writing follows the same shape in reverse. The
{!Pdb.Pdb_builder} module wraps the whole construction in a single
mutable builder so that calling code does not have to assign stream
indices or wire cross-references by hand.

{1 References}

The on-disk format is documented in two places:

- LLVM's [llvm/lib/DebugInfo/PDB] and [llvm/lib/DebugInfo/CodeView]
  trees, with high-level prose at
  {{:https://llvm.org/docs/PDB/}https://llvm.org/docs/PDB/}.
- Microsoft's [microsoft/microsoft-pdb] repository
  ({{:https://github.com/microsoft/microsoft-pdb}https://github.com/microsoft/microsoft-pdb}),
  which is a historical source-code dump rather than a specification
  but is the authoritative reference.

Per-module references (LLVM file paths, specific struct names) live
in the code comments of each [.ml] file.
